'''Alethiology''' (or '''alethology''', "the study of [[aletheia]]") literally means the ''study of [[truth]]'', but can more accurately be translated as ''the study of the nature of truth''.|<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/alethiology |title=Alethiology |encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionaries (online) |accessdate=10 September 2018}}</ref>
==History== It could be argued that ''alethiology'' synonymous with ''[[epistemology]]'', the study of knowledge, and that dividing the two is mere [[semantics]], but sometimes a distinction is made between the two. Epistemology is the study of knowledge and its acquisition. Alethiology is specifically concerned with the ''nature'' of truth, which is only one of the areas studied by epistemologists.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}
The term ''alethiology'' is rare. The ten-volume ''[[Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]'' mentions it only once, in the article "Lambert, Johann Heinrich (1728–77)": {{quote|Part Two of the ''Neues Organon'' is the 'Alethiology or Doctrine of Truth'. Lambert’s key concern here is with the nature and function of the simple concepts that serve as the building blocks for the logical construction of true propositions.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Lambert, Johann Heinrich (1728–77)|encyclopedia=Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy |edition=1.0 |location=London |publisher=Routledge |year=1998 |isbn=978-0415073103}} {{full|date=September 2018|reason=year, volume, page}}</ref>}}
The [[Encyclopædia Britannica Eleventh Edition]] describes the discipline as "…an uncommon expression for the doctrine of truth, used by [[Sir William Hamilton, 9th Baronet|Sir William Hamilton]] in his philosophic writings when treating of the rules for the discrimination of truth and error."<ref>{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Alethiology |volume=1 |page=543}}</ref>
The term appears in ''The Banalization of Nihilism'' (pp. 17–18) in contrast to several other types of nihilism, especially epistemological nihilism. The views of several philosophers are then distinguished by reference to 'alethiological nihilism', 'epistemological nihilism' and the like.<ref>{{cite book |last=Karr |first=Karen L. |title=The Banalization of Nihilism |publisher=State University of New York Press |year=1992 |isbn=0-7914-0833-7}}</ref>
